lang="diq" style="unicode-bidi:embed"><a href="/w/index.php?title=Diq:Map_Features&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Diq:Map Features (page does not exist)">Zazaki</a></span></span>      </div>
</div>
<div class="NavFrame" style="clear:none;margin:0;border:none;padding:0;display:none;"></div></div>
<p>OpenStreetMap represents physical <a href="/wiki/Features" title="Features">features</a> on the ground (e.g., roads or buildings) using <a href="/wiki/Tags" title="Tags">tags</a> attached to its basic data structures (its <a href="/wiki/Nodes" title="Nodes" class="mw-redirect">nodes</a>, <a href="/wiki/Ways" title="Ways" class="mw-redirect">ways</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Relations" title="Relations" class="mw-redirect">relations</a>). Each tag describes a geographic attribute of the feature being shown by that specific node, way or relation. 
</p><p>OpenStreetMap's <a href="/wiki/Tags" title="Tags">free tagging system</a> allows the map to include an unlimited number of attributes describing each feature. The community agrees on certain key and value combinations for the most commonly used tags, which act as informal standards. However, users can create new tags to improve the style of the map or to support analyses that rely on previously unmapped attributes of the features. Short descriptions of tags that relate to particular topics or interests can be found using the <a href="/wiki/Category:Features" title="Category:Features">feature pages</a>.
</p><p>Most features can be described using only a small number of tags, such as a path with a classification tag such as <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:highway" title="Key:highway">highway</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:highway%3Dfootway" title="Tag:highway=footway">footway</a></tt>, and perhaps also a name using <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:name" title="Key:name">name</a>=*</tt>. But, since this is a worldwide, inclusive map, there can be many different feature types in OpenStreetMap, almost all of them described by tags.
</p><p>For details of more tags and proposed changes to existing tags see <a href="/wiki/Proposed_features" title="Proposed features" class="mw-redirect">Proposed features</a> and <a href="/wiki/Deprecated_features" title="Deprecated features">Deprecated features</a>. If you do not find a suitable tag in this list then feel free to make something suitable up as long as the tag values will be <a href="/wiki/Verifiability" title="Verifiability">verifiable</a>. Over time, you may find that the tag name is changed to fit with some wider consensus, however many good tags were used first and documented later.  Information about OSM tags is available as a machine-readable <a href="/wiki/OSMSemanticNetwork" title="OSMSemanticNetwork" class="mw-redirect">semantic network</a>.
</p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Primary_features">Primary features</span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Aerialway">Aerialway</span></h3>
<p>Aerialways cover forms of transport for people or goods using aerial wires including cable-cars, chair-lifts and drag-lifts. See <a href="/wiki/Aerialway" title="Aerialway">Aerialway</a> for an introduction.
</p>
<table class="wikitable sortable" border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2">

<tr style="background-color:#F8F4C2">
<th class="unsortable" style="width:70px"> Key
</th>
<th style="width:100px"> Value
</th>
<th class="unsortable" style="width:70px"> Element
</th>
<th class="unsortable"> Comment
</th>
<th class="unsortable" style="width:100px"> Rendering
</th>
<th class="unsortable" style="width:100px"> Photo
</th></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:aerialway" title="Key:aerialway"> aerialway</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:aerialway%3Dcable_car" title="Tag:aerialway=cable car"> cable_car</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Way" title="Way"><img alt="Way" src="/w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/20px-Osm_element_way.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/30px-Osm_element_way.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/40px-Osm_element_way.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aerial_tramway" class="extiw" title="wikipedia:Aerial tramway">cablecar or tramway</a>. Just one or two large cars. The cable forms a loop, but the cars do not loop around, they just move up and down on their own side.
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Mapping-Features-Aerialway.png" class="image"><img alt="Mapping-Features-Aerialway.png" src="/w/images/thumb/c/c5/Mapping-Features-Aerialway.png/100px-Mapping-Features-Aerialway.png" width="100" height="73" srcset="/w/images/thumb/c/c5/Mapping-Features-Aerialway.png/150px-Mapping-Features-Aerialway.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/c/c5/Mapping-Features-Aerialway.png/200px-Mapping-Features-Aerialway.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td>  <div class="center"><div class="floatnone"><a href="/wiki/File:CH_Furtschellas_aerial_tram.jpg" class="image"><img alt="CH Furtschellas aerial tram.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/f/f8/CH_Furtschellas_aerial_tram.jpg/100px-CH_Furtschellas_aerial_tram.jpg" width="100" height="67" srcset="/w/images/thumb/f/f8/CH_Furtschellas_aerial_tram.jpg/150px-CH_Furtschellas_aerial_tram.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/f/f8/CH_Furtschellas_aerial_tram.jpg/200px-CH_Furtschellas_aerial_tram.jpg 2x" /></a></div></div>

<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:aerialway" title="Key:aerialway"> aerialway</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:aerialway%3Dchair_lift" title="Tag:aerialway=chair lift"> chair_lift</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Way" title="Way"><img alt="Way" src="/w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/20px-Osm_element_way.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/30px-Osm_element_way.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/40px-Osm_element_way.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chairlift" class="extiw" title="wikipedia:Chairlift">chairlift</a>. Looped cable with a series of single chairs (typically seating two or four people, but can be more). Exposed to the open air.  This implies <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:oneway" title="Key:oneway">oneway</a>=yes</tt>.  Any two-way chairlifts should be tagged <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:oneway" title="Key:oneway">oneway</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:oneway%3Dno" title="Tag:oneway=no" class="mw-redirect">no</a></tt>.
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Chair_lift_rendering.png" class="image"><img alt="Chair lift rendering.png" src="/w/images/thumb/8/85/Chair_lift_rendering.png/100px-Chair_lift_rendering.png" width="100" height="100" srcset="/w/images/thumb/8/85/Chair_lift_rendering.png/150px-Chair_lift_rendering.png 1.5x, /w/images/8/85/Chair_lift_rendering.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Silver_Queen_Chair,_CBMR.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Silver Queen Chair, CBMR.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/2/27/Silver_Queen_Chair%2C_CBMR.jpg/100px-Silver_Queen_Chair%2C_CBMR.jpg" width="100" height="66" srcset="/w/images/thumb/2/27/Silver_Queen_Chair%2C_CBMR.jpg/150px-Silver_Queen_Chair%2C_CBMR.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/2/27/Silver_Queen_Chair%2C_CBMR.jpg/200px-Silver_Queen_Chair%2C_CBMR.jpg 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:aerialway" title="Key:aerialway"> aerialway</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:aerialway%3Ddrag_lift" title="Tag:aerialway=drag lift"> drag_lift</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Way" title="Way"><img alt="Way" src="/w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/20px-Osm_element_way.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/30px-Osm_element_way.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/40px-Osm_element_way.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> An overhead tow-line for skiers and riders. A T-bar lift, button lift, or more simple looped rope drag lifts, or loops of wire with handles to grab. See also <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:aerialway" title="Key:aerialway">aerialway</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:aerialway%3Dt-bar" title="Tag:aerialway=t-bar">t-bar</a></tt>, <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:aerialway" title="Key:aerialway">aerialway</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:aerialway%3Dj-bar" title="Tag:aerialway=j-bar">j-bar</a></tt> and <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:aerialway" title="Key:aerialway">aerialway</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:aerialway%3Dplatter" title="Tag:aerialway=platter">platter</a></tt>.
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Chair_lift_rendering.png" class="image"><img alt="Chair lift rendering.png" src="/w/images/thumb/8/85/Chair_lift_rendering.png/100px-Chair_lift_rendering.png" width="100" height="100" srcset="/w/images/thumb/8/85/Chair_lift_rendering.png/150px-Chair_lift_rendering.png 1.5x, /w/images/8/85/Chair_lift_rendering.png 2x" /></a>
</td>

<p><span style="font-size:80%;line-height:120%">This table is a wiki template with a default description in English. <a href="/wiki/Template:Map_Features:aerialway" title="Template:Map Features:aerialway">Editable here</a>.</span>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Aeroway">Aeroway</span></h3>
<p>Mainly relating to aerodromes, airfields other ground facilities to support the operation of airplanes and helicopters. See <a href="/wiki/Aeroways" title="Aeroways">Aeroways</a> for an introduction to the mapping these features.
</p>
<table class="wikitable sortable" border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2">

<tr style="background-colour:#F8F4C2">
<th style="width:70px"> Key
</th>
<th style="width:100px"> Value
</th>
<th class="unsortable" style="width:70px"> Element
</th>
<th class="unsortable"> Comment
</th>
<th class="unsortable" style="width:100px"> Rendering
</th>
<th class="unsortable" style="width:100px"> Photo
</th></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:aeroway" title="Key:aeroway"> aeroway</a>
</td>

<p><span style="font-size:80%;line-height:120%">This table is a wiki template with a default description in English. <a href="/wiki/Template:Map_Features:aeroway" title="Template:Map Features:aeroway">Editable here</a>.</span>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Amenity">Amenity</span></h3>
<p>Used to map facilities for visitors and residents: toilets, telephones, banks, pharmacies (to buy medicines), schools. See <a href="/wiki/Amenities" title="Amenities">Amenities</a> for an introduction.
</p>

<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Mf_node.png" class="image"><img alt="Mf node.png" src="/w/images/b/b5/Mf_node.png" width="20" height="20" /></a>
</td>
<td> A public grill for cooking meat or vegetables, most typically to eat outdoors. Use <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:fuel" title="Key:fuel">fuel</a>=*</tt> to specify source of heating. For campfires and firepits, use <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:leisure" title="Key:leisure">leisure</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:leisure%3Dfirepit" title="Tag:leisure=firepit">firepit</a></tt>
</td>
<td>
</td>
<td>  <div class="center"><div class="floatnone"><a href="/wiki/File:Grillplatzusa.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Grillplatzusa.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/a/aa/Grillplatzusa.jpg/100px-Grillplatzusa.jpg" width="100" height="67" srcset="/w/images/thumb/a/aa/Grillplatzusa.jpg/150px-Grillplatzusa.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/a/aa/Grillplatzusa.jpg/200px-Grillplatzusa.jpg 2x" /></a></div></div>
</td></tr>

Group multiple parking entrances together with a relation using the tags  <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:type" title="Key:type">type</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:type%3Dsite" title="Tag:type=site" class="mw-redirect">site</a></tt> and <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:site" title="Key:site" class="mw-redirect">site</a>=<a href="/w/index.php?title=Tag:site%3Dparking&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Tag:site=parking (page does not exist)">parking</a></tt>.Do <b>not</b> mix with <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:amenity" title="Key:amenity">amenity</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:amenity%3Dparking" title="Tag:amenity=parking">parking</a></tt>.
</td>

<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:amenity" title="Key:amenity"> amenity</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:amenity%3Dparking_space" title="Tag:amenity=parking space"> parking_space</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Mf_node.png" class="image"><img alt="Mf node.png" src="/w/images/b/b5/Mf_node.png" width="20" height="20" /></a> <a href="/wiki/File:Mf_area.png" class="image"><img alt="Mf area.png" src="/w/images/8/83/Mf_area.png" width="20" height="20" /></a>
</td>
<td> A single parking space. Group multiple parking spaces together with a relation using the tags  <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:type" title="Key:type">type</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:type%3Dsite" title="Tag:type=site" class="mw-redirect">site</a></tt> and <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:site" title="Key:site" class="mw-redirect">site</a>=<a href="/w/index.php?title=Tag:site%3Dparking&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Tag:site=parking (page does not exist)">parking</a></tt>.Do <b>not</b> mix with <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:amenity" title="Key:amenity">amenity</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:amenity%3Dparking" title="Tag:amenity=parking">parking</a></tt>.
</td>
<td>
</td>
<td>  <div class="center"><div class="floatnone"><a href="/wiki/File:138081166_2a56d66c27_b.jpg" class="image"><img alt="138081166 2a56d66c27 b.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/d/d7/138081166_2a56d66c27_b.jpg/100px-138081166_2a56d66c27_b.jpg" width="100" height="75" srcset="/w/images/thumb/d/d7/138081166_2a56d66c27_b.jpg/150px-138081166_2a56d66c27_b.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/d/d7/138081166_2a56d66c27_b.jpg/200px-138081166_2a56d66c27_b.jpg 2x" /></a></div></div>
</td></tr>

<p><span style="font-size:80%;line-height:120%">This table is a wiki template with a default description in English. <a href="/wiki/Template:Map_Features:amenity" title="Template:Map Features:amenity">Editable here</a>.</span>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Barrier">Barrier</span></h3>
<p>Used to describe barriers and obstacles to travel. See <a href="/wiki/Barriers" title="Barriers">Barriers</a> for more details on usage.
</p>

<tr style="background-color:#F8F4C2">

<tr>
<th colspan="7"> Linear barriers
</th></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:barrier" title="Key:barrier"> barrier</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:barrier%3Dcity_wall" title="Tag:barrier=city wall"> city_wall</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Way" title="Way"><img alt="Way" src="/w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/20px-Osm_element_way.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/30px-Osm_element_way.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/40px-Osm_element_way.svg.png 2x" /></a> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A fortification used to defend a city or settlement from potential aggressors. <br />From ancient to modern times, they are used to enclose settlements.
<ul>
<li> right side is bottom, left side is top. if both sides are same height then add "two_sided=yes".
</li>
</ul>
<p>See also <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:historic" title="Key:historic">historic</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:historic%3Dcity_gate" title="Tag:historic=city gate">city_gate</a></tt>.
</p>
</td>
<td>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:City_wall_avila.png" class="image"><img alt="City wall avila.png" src="/w/images/thumb/9/94/City_wall_avila.png/100px-City_wall_avila.png" width="100" height="55" srcset="/w/images/thumb/9/94/City_wall_avila.png/150px-City_wall_avila.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/9/94/City_wall_avila.png/200px-City_wall_avila.png 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:barrier" title="Key:barrier"> barrier</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:barrier%3Dditch" title="Tag:barrier=ditch"> ditch</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Way" title="Way"><img alt="Way" src="/w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/20px-Osm_element_way.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/30px-Osm_element_way.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/40px-Osm_element_way.svg.png 2x" /></a> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A trench, ditch or ravine, usually with a stream at the bottom, that is not easily crossed, especially if not on foot. <br />Can be used in combination with <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:waterway" title="Key:waterway">waterway</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:waterway%3Dstream" title="Tag:waterway=stream">stream</a></tt> or <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:waterway" title="Key:waterway">waterway</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:waterway%3Ddrain" title="Tag:waterway=drain">drain</a></tt>.
</td>
<td>
</td>
<td>  <div class="center"><div class="floatnone"><a href="/wiki/File:Forest_ditch.JPG" class="image"><img alt="Forest ditch.JPG" src="/w/images/thumb/5/53/Forest_ditch.JPG/100px-Forest_ditch.JPG" width="100" height="75" srcset="/w/images/thumb/5/53/Forest_ditch.JPG/150px-Forest_ditch.JPG 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/5/53/Forest_ditch.JPG/200px-Forest_ditch.JPG 2x" /></a></div></div>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:barrier" title="Key:barrier"> barrier</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:barrier%3Dfence" title="Tag:barrier=fence"> fence</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Way" title="Way"><img alt="Way" src="/w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/20px-Osm_element_way.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/30px-Osm_element_way.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/40px-Osm_element_way.svg.png 2x" /></a> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A structure supported by posts driven into the ground and designed to prevent movement across a boundary. It is distinguished from a wall by the lightness of its construction. Use <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:fence_type" title="Key:fence type">fence_type</a>=*</tt> to add details.
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Barrier_fence_mapnik.png" class="image"><img alt="Barrier fence mapnik.png" src="/w/images/a/a8/Barrier_fence_mapnik.png" width="100" height="84" /></a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Anglerise.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Anglerise.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/8/88/Anglerise.jpg/100px-Anglerise.jpg" width="100" height="65" srcset="/w/images/thumb/8/88/Anglerise.jpg/150px-Anglerise.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/8/88/Anglerise.jpg/200px-Anglerise.jpg 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:barrier" title="Key:barrier"> barrier</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:barrier%3Dguard_rail" title="Tag:barrier=guard rail"> guard_rail</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Way" title="Way"><img alt="Way" src="/w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/20px-Osm_element_way.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/30px-Osm_element_way.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/40px-Osm_element_way.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A guard_rail, also called a crash barrier. Right side is inner, left side is outer.
</td>
<td>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:CrashBarrier.jpg" class="image"><img alt="CrashBarrier.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/1/1f/CrashBarrier.jpg/100px-CrashBarrier.jpg" width="100" height="75" srcset="/w/images/thumb/1/1f/CrashBarrier.jpg/150px-CrashBarrier.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/1/1f/CrashBarrier.jpg/200px-CrashBarrier.jpg 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:barrier" title="Key:barrier"> barrier</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:barrier%3Dhedge" title="Tag:barrier=hedge"> hedge</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Way" title="Way"><img alt="Way" src="/w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/20px-Osm_element_way.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/30px-Osm_element_way.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/40px-Osm_element_way.svg.png 2x" /></a> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> is a line of closely spaced shrubs and bushes, planted and trained in such a way as to form a barrier or to mark the boundary of an area.
</td>
<td>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Daniel_Fuchs.CC-BY-SA.Morus_nigra.Hedge.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Daniel Fuchs.CC-BY-SA.Morus nigra.Hedge.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/5/55/Daniel_Fuchs.CC-BY-SA.Morus_nigra.Hedge.jpg/100px-Daniel_Fuchs.CC-BY-SA.Morus_nigra.Hedge.jpg" width="100" height="75" srcset="/w/images/thumb/5/55/Daniel_Fuchs.CC-BY-SA.Morus_nigra.Hedge.jpg/150px-Daniel_Fuchs.CC-BY-SA.Morus_nigra.Hedge.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/5/55/Daniel_Fuchs.CC-BY-SA.Morus_nigra.Hedge.jpg/200px-Daniel_Fuchs.CC-BY-SA.Morus_nigra.Hedge.jpg 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:barrier" title="Key:barrier"> barrier</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:barrier%3Dkerb" title="Tag:barrier=kerb"> kerb</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Node" title="Node"><img alt="Node" src="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/20px-Osm_element_node.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/30px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/40px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 2x" /></a> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Way" title="Way"><img alt="Way" src="/w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/20px-Osm_element_way.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/30px-Osm_element_way.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/40px-Osm_element_way.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A (for example footway) kerb is a barrier for vehicles and wheelchair drivers. The height of the kerb is important and with this information, the usage by different groups can be determined. The height of the kerb is tagged additionally as <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:height" title="Key:height">height</a>=*</tt>, if available. Right side is bottom, left side is top.
</td>
<td>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Obrubnik.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Obrubnik.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/f/f8/Obrubnik.jpg/100px-Obrubnik.jpg" width="100" height="133" srcset="/w/images/thumb/f/f8/Obrubnik.jpg/150px-Obrubnik.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/f/f8/Obrubnik.jpg/200px-Obrubnik.jpg 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:barrier" title="Key:barrier"> barrier</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:barrier%3Dretaining_wall" title="Tag:barrier=retaining wall"> retaining_wall</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Way" title="Way"><img alt="Way" src="/w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/20px-Osm_element_way.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/30px-Osm_element_way.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/40px-Osm_element_way.svg.png 2x" /></a> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> Retaining walls serve to retain the lateral pressure of soil. Right side is bottom, left side is top.
</td>
<td>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Retaining_wall.png" class="image"><img alt="Retaining wall.png" src="/w/images/thumb/d/dd/Retaining_wall.png/100px-Retaining_wall.png" width="100" height="75" srcset="/w/images/thumb/d/dd/Retaining_wall.png/150px-Retaining_wall.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/d/dd/Retaining_wall.png/200px-Retaining_wall.png 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:barrier" title="Key:barrier"> barrier</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:barrier%3Dwall" title="Tag:barrier=wall"> wall</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Way" title="Way"><img alt="Way" src="/w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/20px-Osm_element_way.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/30px-Osm_element_way.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/40px-Osm_element_way.svg.png 2x" /></a> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> a freestanding solid structure designed to restrict or prevent movement across a boundary.  Usually made from solid brick, concrete or stone and almost always built so that it is opaque to vision.
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Wallonmap.png" class="image"><img alt="Wallonmap.png" src="/w/images/thumb/b/b0/Wallonmap.png/150px-Wallonmap.png" width="150" height="117" srcset="/w/images/thumb/b/b0/Wallonmap.png/225px-Wallonmap.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/b/b0/Wallonmap.png/300px-Wallonmap.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Dscf0590-800.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Dscf0590-800.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/0/0b/Dscf0590-800.jpg/100px-Dscf0590-800.jpg" width="100" height="82" srcset="/w/images/thumb/0/0b/Dscf0590-800.jpg/150px-Dscf0590-800.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/0/0b/Dscf0590-800.jpg/200px-Dscf0590-800.jpg 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<th colspan="7"> Access control on highways
</th></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:barrier" title="Key:barrier"> barrier</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:barrier%3Dblock" title="Tag:barrier=block"> block</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Node" title="Node"><img alt="Node" src="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/20px-Osm_element_node.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/30px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/40px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A large, solid, immobile block that can be moved only with heavy machinery or great effort. <br />Typically big solid things made of concrete for stopping larger vehicles. <br />Sometimes natural boulders are used for the same purpose.
</td>
<td>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Barrier_roadblock.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Barrier roadblock.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/6/64/Barrier_roadblock.jpg/100px-Barrier_roadblock.jpg" width="100" height="75" srcset="/w/images/thumb/6/64/Barrier_roadblock.jpg/150px-Barrier_roadblock.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/6/64/Barrier_roadblock.jpg/200px-Barrier_roadblock.jpg 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:barrier" title="Key:barrier"> barrier</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:barrier%3Dbollard" title="Tag:barrier=bollard"> bollard</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Node" title="Node"><img alt="Node" src="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/20px-Osm_element_node.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/30px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/40px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 2x" /></a> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Way" title="Way"><img alt="Way" src="/w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/20px-Osm_element_way.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/30px-Osm_element_way.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/40px-Osm_element_way.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> solid (usually concrete or metal) pillar or pillars in the middle of the road to prevent passage by some traffic.
</td>
<td>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Bollard_in_residential_area.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Bollard in residential area.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/c/c5/Bollard_in_residential_area.jpg/100px-Bollard_in_residential_area.jpg" width="100" height="97" srcset="/w/images/thumb/c/c5/Bollard_in_residential_area.jpg/150px-Bollard_in_residential_area.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/c/c5/Bollard_in_residential_area.jpg/200px-Bollard_in_residential_area.jpg 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:barrier" title="Key:barrier"> barrier</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:barrier%3Dborder_control" title="Tag:barrier=border control"> border_control</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Node" title="Node"><img alt="Node" src="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/20px-Osm_element_node.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/30px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/40px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> This is a control point at an international border between two countries.  Passports or other forms of ID will be checked.
</td>
<td>
</td>
<td>  <a href="/wiki/File:EU_Swiss_border_post.jpg" class="image"><img alt="EU Swiss border post.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/e/ed/EU_Swiss_border_post.jpg/100px-EU_Swiss_border_post.jpg" width="100" height="67" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/ed/EU_Swiss_border_post.jpg/150px-EU_Swiss_border_post.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/ed/EU_Swiss_border_post.jpg/200px-EU_Swiss_border_post.jpg 2x" /></a>

<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:barrier%3Dcattle_grid" title="Tag:barrier=cattle grid"> cattle_grid</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Node" title="Node"><img alt="Node" src="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/20px-Osm_element_node.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/30px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/40px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> Bars in the road surface that allow wheeled vehicles but not animals to cross. <br />Sometimes known as a Texas Gate, even outside of Texas
</td>
<td>
</td>
<td> <div class="center"><div class="floatnone"><a href="/wiki/File:Cattle_grid.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Cattle grid.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e2/Cattle_grid.jpg/100px-Cattle_grid.jpg" width="100" height="75" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e2/Cattle_grid.jpg/150px-Cattle_grid.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e2/Cattle_grid.jpg/200px-Cattle_grid.jpg 2x" /></a></div></div>
</td></tr>

</td>
<td> A chain used to prevent motorised vehicles.
</td>

</td>

</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Node" title="Node"><img alt="Node" src="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/20px-Osm_element_node.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/30px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/40px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> Barriers to bicycle traffic, most typically a pair of staggered steel bars perpendicular to the way itself whose gaps allow pedestrians to pass.
</td>

</td>

<td> <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tag:barrier%3Ddebris&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Tag:barrier=debris (page does not exist)"> debris</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Node" title="Node"><img alt="Node" src="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/20px-Osm_element_node.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/30px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/40px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A road is blocked by debris with or without ground. This might be for short or long time. Often used as first step in blocking an abandoned road. The photo does not display the road after the debris because it was a slope road and the photo was taken on the top.
</td>

</td>
<td> A gap in a linear barrier with nothing that limits passing through. <br /><tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:access" title="Key:access">access</a>=yes</tt> is understood. <br />The limitations are the same of the way that crosses it, if there is such.

<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Node" title="Node"><img alt="Node" src="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/20px-Osm_element_node.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/30px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/40px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 2x" /></a>

</td>
<td> A <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jersey_barrier" class="extiw" title="wikipedia:Jersey barrier">jersey barrier</a> consists of heavy prefabricated blocks to create a barrier. Use <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:material" title="Key:material">material</a>=plastic</tt> or <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:material" title="Key:material">material</a>=concrete</tt> to express the used material.

</td>
<td> A Kent carriage gap is used by local authorities in the UK to prevent motorised vehicles from accessing public rights of way whilst allowing most horse drawn carriages to pass. <br />These are now becoming common on byways in the UK

</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Node" title="Node"><img alt="Node" src="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/20px-Osm_element_node.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/30px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/40px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 2x" /></a> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Way" title="Way"><img alt="Way" src="/w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/20px-Osm_element_way.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/30px-Osm_element_way.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/40px-Osm_element_way.svg.png 2x" /></a>

<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:barrier%3Dspikes" title="Tag:barrier=spikes" class="mw-redirect"> spikes</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Node" title="Node"><img alt="Node" src="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/20px-Osm_element_node.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/30px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/40px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 2x" /></a> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Way" title="Way"><img alt="Way" src="/w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/20px-Osm_element_way.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/30px-Osm_element_way.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/ee/Osm_element_way.svg/40px-Osm_element_way.svg.png 2x" /></a> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> Spikes on the ground that prevent unauthorized access. Can also be removeable e.g. after payment in a garage.
</td>
<td>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:US_Army_spike_strip.jpg" class="image"><img alt="US Army spike strip.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/6/65/US_Army_spike_strip.jpg/100px-US_Army_spike_strip.jpg" width="100" height="149" srcset="/w/images/thumb/6/65/US_Army_spike_strip.jpg/150px-US_Army_spike_strip.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/6/65/US_Army_spike_strip.jpg/200px-US_Army_spike_strip.jpg 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:barrier" title="Key:barrier"> barrier</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:barrier%3Dstile" title="Tag:barrier=stile"> stile</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Node" title="Node"><img alt="Node" src="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/20px-Osm_element_node.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/30px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/40px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A stile allows pedestrians to cross a wall or fence, but never actually "opens" the barrier <br />(unlike a gate, a stile has few or no moving parts).
</td>
<td>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:KentStile.jpg" class="image"><img alt="KentStile.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/0/0f/KentStile.jpg/100px-KentStile.jpg" width="100" height="67" srcset="/w/images/thumb/0/0f/KentStile.jpg/150px-KentStile.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/0/0f/KentStile.jpg/200px-KentStile.jpg 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:barrier" title="Key:barrier"> barrier</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:barrier%3Dsump_buster" title="Tag:barrier=sump buster"> sump_buster</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Node" title="Node"><img alt="Node" src="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/20px-Osm_element_node.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/30px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/40px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sump_buster" class="extiw" title="wikipedia:Sump buster">sump buster</a> is a concrete slab or steel structure that prevents passing of two-tracked vehicles with less than a minimum track and ground clearance. (Typically stops normal cars.)
</td>
<td>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:SumpBuster.jpg" class="image"><img alt="SumpBuster.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/8/8a/SumpBuster.jpg/100px-SumpBuster.jpg" width="100" height="75" srcset="/w/images/thumb/8/8a/SumpBuster.jpg/150px-SumpBuster.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/8/8a/SumpBuster.jpg/200px-SumpBuster.jpg 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:barrier" title="Key:barrier"> barrier</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:barrier%3Dswing_gate" title="Tag:barrier=swing gate"> swing_gate</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Node" title="Node"><img alt="Node" src="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/20px-Osm_element_node.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/30px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/40px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> Similar to a lift gate but rotates sidewards to open. It is usually made out of metal bars (wood or other material possible) and is intended to prevent cars from access but can usually be crossed by pedestrians and cyclists.
</td>
<td>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:16052010022.JPG" class="image"><img alt="16052010022.JPG" src="/w/images/thumb/9/97/16052010022.JPG/100px-16052010022.JPG" width="100" height="56" srcset="/w/images/thumb/9/97/16052010022.JPG/150px-16052010022.JPG 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/9/97/16052010022.JPG/200px-16052010022.JPG 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:barrier" title="Key:barrier"> barrier</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:barrier%3Dtoll_booth" title="Tag:barrier=toll booth"> toll_booth</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Node" title="Node"><img alt="Node" src="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/20px-Osm_element_node.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/30px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/40px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A road usage toll or fee is collected here.
</td>
<td>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Toll_booth.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Toll booth.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/c/cd/Toll_booth.jpg/100px-Toll_booth.jpg" width="100" height="75" srcset="/w/images/thumb/c/cd/Toll_booth.jpg/150px-Toll_booth.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/c/cd/Toll_booth.jpg/200px-Toll_booth.jpg 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:barrier" title="Key:barrier"> barrier</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:barrier%3Dturnstile" title="Tag:barrier=turnstile"> turnstile</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Node" title="Node"><img alt="Node" src="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/20px-Osm_element_node.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/30px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/7/76/Osm_element_node.svg/40px-Osm_element_node.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A turnstile (also called baffle gate) is used to allow one person at a time to pass. Use this for small turnstiles like the ones in supermarkets or some subways.
</td>
<td>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Barrier_drehkreuz.JPG" class="image"><img alt="Barrier drehkreuz.JPG" src="/w/images/thumb/1/18/Barrier_drehkreuz.JPG/100px-Barrier_drehkreuz.JPG" width="100" height="103" srcset="/w/images/thumb/1/18/Barrier_drehkreuz.JPG/150px-Barrier_drehkreuz.JPG 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/1/18/Barrier_drehkreuz.JPG/200px-Barrier_drehkreuz.JPG 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Boundary">Boundary</span></h3>
<p>Used to describe administrative and other boundaries. See <a href="/wiki/Boundaries" title="Boundaries">Boundaries</a> for more details.
</p>
<table class="wikitable sortable" border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2">

<tr style="background-color:#F8F4C2">
<th style="width:70px"> Key
</th>
<th style="width:100px"> Value
</th>
<th style="width:70px"> Element
</th>
<th> Comment
</th>
<th style="width:100px"> Rendering
</th>

<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:boundary" title="Key:boundary"> boundary</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:boundary%3Dadministrative" title="Tag:boundary=administrative"> administrative</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td>  An administrative boundary. Subdivisions of areas/territories/jurisdictions recognised by governments or other organisations for administrative purposes.  These range from large groups of nation states right down to small administrative districts and suburbs, as indicated by the '<tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:admin_level" title="Key:admin level" class="mw-redirect">admin_level</a>=*</tt>' combo tag
</td>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Building">Building</span></h3>
<p>Used to identify individual buildings or groups of connected buildings. See <a href="/wiki/Buildings" title="Buildings">Buildings</a> for further details of usage of this tag and <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:man_made" title="Key:man made">man_made</a>=*</tt> for tagging of various other structures.
</p>
<table class="wikitable sortable" border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2">

<tr style="background-color:#F8F4C2">
<th style="width:70px"> Key
</th>
<th style="width:100px"> Value
</th>
<th class="unsortable" style="width:70px"> Element
</th>
<th class="unsortable"> Comment
</th>
<th class="unsortable" style="width:100px"> Photo
</th></tr>
<tr>
<th colspan="7"> Accommodation
</th></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:building" title="Key:building"> building</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dapartments" title="Tag:building=apartments"> apartments</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A building arranged into individual dwellings, often on separate floors. May also have retail outlets on the ground floor. How does one map the retail elements? Use <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:building:levels" title="Key:building:levels">building:levels</a>=*</tt> for the total number of floors.
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Apartments6levels.png" class="image"><img alt="Apartments6levels.png" src="/w/images/thumb/7/7d/Apartments6levels.png/100px-Apartments6levels.png" width="100" height="149" srcset="/w/images/thumb/7/7d/Apartments6levels.png/150px-Apartments6levels.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/7/7d/Apartments6levels.png/200px-Apartments6levels.png 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:building" title="Key:building"> building</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Ddormitory" title="Tag:building=dormitory"> dormitory</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> For a shared building, as used by college/university students (not a share room for multiple occupants as implied by the term in British English). Would 'hall_of_residence' be better?
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Belgrade_Dormitory.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Belgrade Dormitory.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/2/28/Belgrade_Dormitory.jpg/100px-Belgrade_Dormitory.jpg" width="100" height="75" srcset="/w/images/thumb/2/28/Belgrade_Dormitory.jpg/150px-Belgrade_Dormitory.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/2/28/Belgrade_Dormitory.jpg/200px-Belgrade_Dormitory.jpg 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:building" title="Key:building"> building</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dfarm" title="Tag:building=farm"> farm</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A residential building on a farm (farmhouse). For other buildings see below <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:building" title="Key:building">building</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dfarm_auxiliary" title="Tag:building=farm auxiliary">farm_auxiliary</a></tt>, <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:building" title="Key:building">building</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dbarn" title="Tag:building=barn">barn</a></tt>, ... If in your country farmhouse looks same as general residential house then you can tag as <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:building" title="Key:building">building</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dhouse" title="Tag:building=house">house</a></tt> as well. See also <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:landuse" title="Key:landuse">landuse</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:landuse%3Dfarmyard" title="Tag:landuse=farmyard">farmyard</a></tt>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Studna_p%C5%99ed_%C4%8D.1.,Hola%C5%A1ovice.JPG" class="image"><img alt="Studna před č.1.,Holašovice.JPG" src="/w/images/thumb/1/10/Studna_p%C5%99ed_%C4%8D.1.%2CHola%C5%A1ovice.JPG/100px-Studna_p%C5%99ed_%C4%8D.1.%2CHola%C5%A1ovice.JPG" width="100" height="75" srcset="/w/images/thumb/1/10/Studna_p%C5%99ed_%C4%8D.1.%2CHola%C5%A1ovice.JPG/150px-Studna_p%C5%99ed_%C4%8D.1.%2CHola%C5%A1ovice.JPG 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/1/10/Studna_p%C5%99ed_%C4%8D.1.%2CHola%C5%A1ovice.JPG/200px-Studna_p%C5%99ed_%C4%8D.1.%2CHola%C5%A1ovice.JPG 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:building" title="Key:building"> building</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dhotel" title="Tag:building=hotel"> hotel</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A building designed with separate rooms available for overnight accommodation. Normally used in conjunction with <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:tourism" title="Key:tourism">tourism</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:tourism%3Dhotel" title="Tag:tourism=hotel">hotel</a></tt> for the hotel grounds including recreation areas and parking.
</td>
<td><a href="/wiki/File:Hcom_1097758_7_b.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Hcom 1097758 7 b.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/c/ca/Hcom_1097758_7_b.jpg/100px-Hcom_1097758_7_b.jpg" width="100" height="83" srcset="/w/images/thumb/c/ca/Hcom_1097758_7_b.jpg/150px-Hcom_1097758_7_b.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/c/ca/Hcom_1097758_7_b.jpg/200px-Hcom_1097758_7_b.jpg 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:building" title="Key:building"> building</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dhouse" title="Tag:building=house"> house</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A single dwelling unit inhabited by family or small group sharing facilities such as a kitchen. Houses forming half of a semi-detached pair, or one of a row of terraced houses, should share at least two nodes with joined neighbours, thereby defining the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/party_wall" class="extiw" title="wikipedia:party wall">party wall</a> between the properties.
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Emptyhouse.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Emptyhouse.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/6/61/Emptyhouse.jpg/100px-Emptyhouse.jpg" width="100" height="63" srcset="/w/images/thumb/6/61/Emptyhouse.jpg/150px-Emptyhouse.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/6/61/Emptyhouse.jpg/200px-Emptyhouse.jpg 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>

</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A single dwelling unit inhabited by family or small group sharing facilities such as a kitchen.
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Residential_House_USA.JPG" class="image"><img alt="Residential House USA.JPG" src="/w/images/thumb/4/4d/Residential_House_USA.JPG/100px-Residential_House_USA.JPG" width="100" height="75" srcset="/w/images/thumb/4/4d/Residential_House_USA.JPG/150px-Residential_House_USA.JPG 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/4/4d/Residential_House_USA.JPG/200px-Residential_House_USA.JPG 2x" /></a>

<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:building" title="Key:building"> building</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dresidential" title="Tag:building=residential">residential</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A general tag for a building used primarily for residential purposes. Where additional detail is available consider using one or more areas tagged as 'apartments', 'terrace' or 'house'.
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Timarpur_Residential_Complex.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Timarpur Residential Complex.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/0/02/Timarpur_Residential_Complex.jpg/100px-Timarpur_Residential_Complex.jpg" width="100" height="75" srcset="/w/images/thumb/0/02/Timarpur_Residential_Complex.jpg/150px-Timarpur_Residential_Complex.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/0/02/Timarpur_Residential_Complex.jpg/200px-Timarpur_Residential_Complex.jpg 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:building" title="Key:building"> building</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dterrace" title="Tag:building=terrace">terrace</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A single way used to define the outline of a linear row of residential dwellings, each of which normally has its own entrance, which form a terrace (row-house in North American English). Consider defining each dwelling separately using 'house'.
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Terraced_housing.png" class="image"><img alt="Terraced housing.png" src="/w/images/thumb/8/8f/Terraced_housing.png/100px-Terraced_housing.png" width="100" height="66" srcset="/w/images/thumb/8/8f/Terraced_housing.png/150px-Terraced_housing.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/8/8f/Terraced_housing.png/200px-Terraced_housing.png 2x" /></a>

<th colspan="7"> Commercial
</th></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:building" title="Key:building"> building</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dcommercial" title="Tag:building=commercial"> commercial</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A building where non-specific commercial activities take place; use <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:office" title="Key:office">office</a>=*</tt> to describe the type of office. Consider tagging the area using <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:landuse" title="Key:landuse">landuse</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:landuse%3Dcommercial" title="Tag:landuse=commercial">commercial</a></tt>. Use 'retail' if the building consists primarily of shops.
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Buildingoffices.png" class="image"><img alt="Buildingoffices.png" src="/w/images/thumb/9/90/Buildingoffices.png/100px-Buildingoffices.png" width="100" height="76" srcset="/w/images/thumb/9/90/Buildingoffices.png/150px-Buildingoffices.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/9/90/Buildingoffices.png/200px-Buildingoffices.png 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:building" title="Key:building"> building</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dindustrial" title="Tag:building=industrial">industrial</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A building where some industrial process takes place. Use warehouse if the purpose is known to be primarily for storage/distribution. Consider using <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:landuse" title="Key:landuse">landuse</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:landuse%3Dindustrial" title="Tag:landuse=industrial">industrial</a></tt> for the surrounding area and the proposed <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:industrial" title="Key:industrial" class="mw-redirect">industrial</a>=*</tt> tag to describe the industrial activity.
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Eley_Industrial_Estate1.JPG" class="image"><img alt="Eley Industrial Estate1.JPG" src="/w/images/thumb/3/36/Eley_Industrial_Estate1.JPG/100px-Eley_Industrial_Estate1.JPG" width="100" height="66" srcset="/w/images/thumb/3/36/Eley_Industrial_Estate1.JPG/150px-Eley_Industrial_Estate1.JPG 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/3/36/Eley_Industrial_Estate1.JPG/200px-Eley_Industrial_Estate1.JPG 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:building" title="Key:building"> building</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dretail" title="Tag:building=retail">retail</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A building primarily used for selling goods are sold to the public; use <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:shop" title="Key:shop">shop</a>=*</tt> to identify the sort of goods sold. Consider use <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:landuse" title="Key:landuse">landuse</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:landuse%3Dretail" title="Tag:landuse=retail">retail</a></tt> for the surrounding area. How is one meant to indicate that there is also residential accommodation or office use above?
</td>

</td></tr>

<th colspan="7"> Civic/amenity
</th></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:building" title="Key:building"> building</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dcathedral" title="Tag:building=cathedral"> cathedral</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A building that was built as a cathedral. Used in conjunction with <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:amenity" title="Key:amenity">amenity</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:amenity%3Dplace_of_worship" title="Tag:amenity=place of worship">place_of_worship</a></tt>, <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:religion" title="Key:religion">religion</a>=*</tt> and <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:denomination" title="Key:denomination">denomination</a>=*</tt> for the cathedral grounds where it is in current use.
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Saint_Vitus_Cathedral_in_Prague,_Czech_Republic.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Saint Vitus Cathedral in Prague, Czech Republic.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/5/5f/Saint_Vitus_Cathedral_in_Prague%2C_Czech_Republic.jpg/100px-Saint_Vitus_Cathedral_in_Prague%2C_Czech_Republic.jpg" width="100" height="150" srcset="/w/images/thumb/5/5f/Saint_Vitus_Cathedral_in_Prague%2C_Czech_Republic.jpg/150px-Saint_Vitus_Cathedral_in_Prague%2C_Czech_Republic.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/5/5f/Saint_Vitus_Cathedral_in_Prague%2C_Czech_Republic.jpg/200px-Saint_Vitus_Cathedral_in_Prague%2C_Czech_Republic.jpg 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:building" title="Key:building"> building</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dchapel" title="Tag:building=chapel"> chapel</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A building that was built as a chapel. Used in conjunction with <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:amenity" title="Key:amenity">amenity</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:amenity%3Dplace_of_worship" title="Tag:amenity=place of worship">place_of_worship</a></tt>, <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:religion" title="Key:religion">religion</a>=*</tt> and <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:denomination" title="Key:denomination">denomination</a>=*</tt> for the chapel grounds where it is in current use.
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Bevillers_chapel_cemetery.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Bevillers chapel cemetery.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/7/7c/Bevillers_chapel_cemetery.jpg/100px-Bevillers_chapel_cemetery.jpg" width="100" height="75" srcset="/w/images/thumb/7/7c/Bevillers_chapel_cemetery.jpg/150px-Bevillers_chapel_cemetery.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/7/7c/Bevillers_chapel_cemetery.jpg/200px-Bevillers_chapel_cemetery.jpg 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:building" title="Key:building"> building</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dchurch" title="Tag:building=church"> church</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A building that was built as a church. Used in conjunction with <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:amenity" title="Key:amenity">amenity</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:amenity%3Dplace_of_worship" title="Tag:amenity=place of worship">place_of_worship</a></tt>, <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:religion" title="Key:religion">religion</a>=*</tt> and <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:denomination" title="Key:denomination">denomination</a>=*</tt> for the church grounds where it is in current use.
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Churchstcl.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Churchstcl.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/7/7e/Churchstcl.jpg/100px-Churchstcl.jpg" width="100" height="63" srcset="/w/images/thumb/7/7e/Churchstcl.jpg/150px-Churchstcl.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/7/7e/Churchstcl.jpg/200px-Churchstcl.jpg 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:building" title="Key:building"> building</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dcivic" title="Tag:building=civic"> civic</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> For any civic amenity, for example <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:amenity" title="Key:amenity">amenity</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:amenity%3Dcommunity_centre" title="Tag:amenity=community centre">community_centre</a></tt>, <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:amenity" title="Key:amenity">amenity</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:amenity%3Dlibrary" title="Tag:amenity=library">library</a></tt>, <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:amenity" title="Key:amenity">amenity</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:amenity%3Dtoilets" title="Tag:amenity=toilets">toilets</a></tt>, <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:leisure" title="Key:leisure">leisure</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:leisure%3Dsports_centre" title="Tag:leisure=sports centre">sports_centre</a></tt>, <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:leisure" title="Key:leisure">leisure</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:leisure%3Dswimming_pool" title="Tag:leisure=swimming pool">swimming_pool</a></tt>, <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:amenity" title="Key:amenity">amenity</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:amenity%3Dtownhall" title="Tag:amenity=townhall">townhall</a></tt> etc. Use <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:amenity" title="Key:amenity">amenity</a>=*</tt> or <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:leisure" title="Key:leisure">leisure</a>=*</tt> etc to provide further details. See <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:building" title="Key:building">building</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dpublic" title="Tag:building=public">public</a></tt> as well.
</td>
<td><a href="/wiki/File:Scarborough_Civic_Centre.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Scarborough Civic Centre.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e5/Scarborough_Civic_Centre.jpg/100px-Scarborough_Civic_Centre.jpg" width="100" height="66" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e5/Scarborough_Civic_Centre.jpg/150px-Scarborough_Civic_Centre.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e5/Scarborough_Civic_Centre.jpg/200px-Scarborough_Civic_Centre.jpg 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>

<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dhospital" title="Tag:building=hospital">hospital</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A building which forms part of a hospital. Use <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:amenity" title="Key:amenity">amenity</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:amenity%3Dhospital" title="Tag:amenity=hospital">hospital</a></tt> for the hospital grounds.
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Hospital.png" class="image"><img alt="Hospital.png" src="/w/images/thumb/6/66/Hospital.png/100px-Hospital.png" width="100" height="111" srcset="/w/images/thumb/6/66/Hospital.png/150px-Hospital.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/6/66/Hospital.png/200px-Hospital.png 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>

<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:building" title="Key:building"> building</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dschool" title="Tag:building=school">school</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> For any generic school buildings. Buildings for specific uses (sports halls etc) should be tagged for their purpose. Use <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:amenity" title="Key:amenity">amenity</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:amenity%3Dschool" title="Tag:amenity=school">school</a></tt> for the perimeter of the school grounds.
</td>

<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dtransportation" title="Tag:building=transportation">transportation</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A building related to public transport. You will probably want to tag it with proper tranport related tag as well, such as <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:public_transport" title="Key:public transport">public_transport</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:public_transport%3Dstation" title="Tag:public transport=station">station</a></tt>. Note that there is a special tag for train station buildings - <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:building" title="Key:building">building</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dtrain_station" title="Tag:building=train station">train_station</a></tt>.
</td>

<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dbridge" title="Tag:building=bridge"> bridge</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A building used as a bridge. Can also represent a gatehouse for drawbridges. See also <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:bridge" title="Key:bridge">bridge</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:bridge%3Dyes" title="Tag:bridge=yes" class="mw-redirect">yes</a></tt> for <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:highway" title="Key:highway">highway</a>=*</tt>. <b>Don't use this tag just for for marking bridges (their outlines). For such purposes consider the proposed <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:man_made" title="Key:man made">man_made</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:man_made%3Dbridge" title="Tag:man made=bridge">bridge</a></tt></b>.
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Ponte_Veccio1.JPG" class="image"><img alt="Ponte Veccio1.JPG" src="/w/images/thumb/d/d6/Ponte_Veccio1.JPG/100px-Ponte_Veccio1.JPG" width="100" height="76" srcset="/w/images/thumb/d/d6/Ponte_Veccio1.JPG/150px-Ponte_Veccio1.JPG 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/d/d6/Ponte_Veccio1.JPG/200px-Ponte_Veccio1.JPG 2x" /></a>

<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dcabin" title="Tag:building=cabin">cabin</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cabin" class="extiw" title="wikipedia:Cabin">cabin</a> is a small, roughly built house usually with a wood exterior and typically found in rural areas.

<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:building" title="Key:building"> building</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dcowshed" title="Tag:building=cowshed">cowshed</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A cowshed (cow barn, cow house) is a a building for housing cows, usually found on farms.
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Cowhouse_Hrazany2.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Cowhouse Hrazany2.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/f/fb/Cowhouse_Hrazany2.jpg/100px-Cowhouse_Hrazany2.jpg" width="100" height="75" srcset="/w/images/thumb/f/fb/Cowhouse_Hrazany2.jpg/150px-Cowhouse_Hrazany2.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/f/fb/Cowhouse_Hrazany2.jpg/200px-Cowhouse_Hrazany2.jpg 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:building" title="Key:building"> building</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dfarm_auxiliary" title="Tag:building=farm auxiliary"> farm_auxiliary</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A building on a farm that is not a dwelling (use 'house' for the farm house).
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Horseshoe_Barn.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Horseshoe Barn.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/f/f8/Horseshoe_Barn.jpg/100px-Horseshoe_Barn.jpg" width="100" height="75" srcset="/w/images/thumb/f/f8/Horseshoe_Barn.jpg/150px-Horseshoe_Barn.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/f/f8/Horseshoe_Barn.jpg/200px-Horseshoe_Barn.jpg 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:building" title="Key:building"> building</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dgarage" title="Tag:building=garage">garage</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Garage_(house)" class="extiw" title="wikipedia:Garage (house)">garage</a> is a building suitable for the storage of one or possibly more motor vehicle or similar. See <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:building" title="Key:building">building</a>=garages</tt> for larger shared buildings.
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Two-Car_Garage.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Two-Car Garage.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/1/11/Two-Car_Garage.jpg/100px-Two-Car_Garage.jpg" width="100" height="74" srcset="/w/images/thumb/1/11/Two-Car_Garage.jpg/150px-Two-Car_Garage.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/1/11/Two-Car_Garage.jpg/200px-Two-Car_Garage.jpg 2x" /></a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:building" title="Key:building"> building</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dgarages" title="Tag:building=garages">garages </a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A building that consists of a number of discrete storage spaces for different owners/tenants. See also <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:building" title="Key:building">building</a>=garage</tt>.
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:Landbouwstraat_garages.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Landbouwstraat garages.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/d/d8/Landbouwstraat_garages.jpg/100px-Landbouwstraat_garages.jpg" width="100" height="75" srcset="/w/images/thumb/d/d8/Landbouwstraat_garages.jpg/150px-Landbouwstraat_garages.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/d/d8/Landbouwstraat_garages.jpg/200px-Landbouwstraat_garages.jpg 2x" /></a>

<td> <a href="/wiki/Key:building" title="Key:building"> building</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dgreenhouse" title="Tag:building=greenhouse">greenhouse</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greenhouse" class="extiw" title="wikipedia:Greenhouse">greenhouse</a> is a glass or plastic covered building used to grow plants. Use <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:landuse" title="Key:landuse">landuse</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:landuse%3Dgreenhouse_horticulture" title="Tag:landuse=greenhouse horticulture">greenhouse_horticulture</a></tt> for the area
</td>

<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dhangar" title="Tag:building=hangar">hangar</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hangar" class="extiw" title="wikipedia:Hangar">hangar</a> is a building used for the storage of airplanes, helicopters or space-craft. Consider adding <tt style="background-color:#e0e0f0; white-space:pre;" dir="ltr"><a href="/wiki/Key:aeroway" title="Key:aeroway">aeroway</a>=<a href="/wiki/Tag:aeroway%3Dhangar" title="Tag:aeroway=hangar">hangar</a></tt>, when appropriate.

</td>

</td>

<td> <a href="/wiki/Tag:building%3Dshed" title="Tag:building=shed">shed</a>
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/Elements#Area_.28closed_way_.29" title="Area"><img alt="Area" src="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/20px-Osm_element_area.svg.png" width="20" height="20" srcset="/w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/30px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/e/e6/Osm_element_area.svg/40px-Osm_element_area.svg.png 2x" /></a>
</td>
<td> A <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shed" class="extiw" title="wikipedia:Shed">shed</a> is a simple, single-storey structure in a back garden or on an allotment that is used for storage, hobbies, or as a workshop.
</td>

</td>

</td>
<td> A stable is a building where horses are kept.
</td>
<td> <a href="/wiki/File:H%C3%A4ststall_Elfviks_g%C3%A5rd_dec_2008.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Häststall Elfviks gård dec 2008.jpg" src="/w/images/thumb/0/03/H%C3%A4ststall_Elfviks_g%C3%A5rd_dec_2008.jpg/100px-H%C3%A4ststall_Elfviks_g%C3%A5rd_dec_2008.jpg" width="100" height="74" srcset="/w/images/thumb/0/03/H%C3%A4ststall_Elfviks_g%C3%A5rd_dec_2008.jpg/150px-H%C3%A4ststall_Elfviks_g%C3%A5rd_dec_2008.jpg 1.5x, /w/images/thumb/0/03/H%C3%A4ststall_Elfviks_g%C3%A5rd_dec_2008.jpg/200px-H%C3%A4ststall_Elfviks_g%C3%A5rd_dec_2008.jpg 2x" /></a>
